  "prompt": "What happens if you overdose on Naproxen?",
  "response": "An overdose of naproxen, a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID), can lead to serious health complications. Symptoms of a naproxen overdose may include:\n\n1. **Gastrointestinal Symptoms**: Nausea, vomiting, stomach pain, indigestion, or constipation.\n2. **Central Nervous System Effects**: Dizziness, headache, drowsiness, or, in severe cases, confusion or seizures.\n3. **Kidney Issues**: Reduced urine output or signs of kidney dysfunction.\n4. **Cardiovascular Effects**: High blood pressure or heart-related symptoms.\n5. **Liver Damage**: Elevated liver enzyme levels may occur with significant overdose.\n6. **Respiratory Problems**: Difficulty breathing or shortness of breath in severe cases.\n\nIf someone is suspected of having taken an overdose of naproxen, it is crucial to seek medical attention immediately. Treatment may involve supportive care, including monitoring vitals, managing symptoms, and potentially administering activated charcoal if the ingestion was recent.\n\nDo not ignore the situation, as prompt medical intervention is essential for managing the potential complications of an overdose.",
